Conditional statements: 
-> to make the set of instructions (block of code) execute only when the given condition is True
-> used to decide whether the code has to be executed or skip based on the given condition
-> will execute in a sequence (line by line)
-> condition : an expression that evaluates an result (True or false)
ex: console.log(5>6)
Methods : if , if - else, else if, switch, ternary operator
if : only one condition if condition is true it executes otherwise it will skip
syntax : if(condition){ 
              block of code
         }
ex: let a =4
        let b = 5
        if(a<b){
            document.write("hello world","<br>")
        }
        document.write("brilliant chiru")// it executes because it is out of the loop
op : hello world
     brilliant chiru
if-else: 
ex: let a=4
        let b = 5
        if(a>b){
            document.write("hello world","<br>")
        }else {
            document.write("hi sam","<br>")
        }
        document.write("brilliant chiru")
else if :
ex: let age= prompt("enter your age")
        let name = prompt("enter your name")
        if(age<18){
            alert(name +" you are too young to marry")
        }else if(age>35){
            alert(name +" you are too old to marry")
        }else {
            alert(name +" perfect age to marry")
        }
        alert("welcome to my world")
else :
ex : let a = prompt("enter score of a")
        let b = prompt("enter b score")
        let c = a+b
        if((a>300 || b>300) && (c < 500)){
            alert("Can team up")
        }else {
            alert("Cannot team up")
        }
